I appreciate your thoughts. I did try to avoid a direct compulsion effect, in that nobody who is affected on this thing feels like they have to work on this thing, but they're assigned to work on this thing, and therefore, they're going to be subject to its effect. So any random person will accept there are bees in the room and not care, but Edmunson has been assigned to contain these bees, and since he accepts they're in there, everything he's doing is because it's his job, not because he  contents twice and coming up with different results, which wouldn't necessarily happen in a compulsion effect.

This is why they can act a bit ridiculous, because it's ridiculous to hold the view that there are bees in that room, even though that's exactly what's happening. Watching people bend over backwards to avoid the dissonance in their beliefs is always a little funny, which is the core of this article. If Ayim didn't see bees in a room that clearly must have bees in it, perhaps it's because he forgot his reading glasses and therefore would struggle to see tiny things, since that's what reading glasses are for. Certainly a better explanation than there not being bees in the room.

I do appreciate that you liked the origin story. That was the part I was least sure about, so I'm glad to know it didn't mess things up. The idea for the blacked-out SCP actually came before this idea, and I wanted to have a  if I ever decide to write up the 001 proposal that created this SCP room.

Thank you for your thorough feedback.





